03831nam a22004695i 9780804764742DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20201996cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047647427 a10.1515/97808047647422doi  a(DE-B1597)563975  a(OCoLC)1178768931  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a320/.011 aTang, Xiaobing, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGlobal Space and the Nationalist Discourse of Modernity :bThe Historical Thinking of Liang Qichao /cXiaobing Tang. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Toward a Geography of the Discourse of Modernity -- t1. History Imagined Anew: Liang Qichao in 1902 -- t2. The Nationalist Historian and New Historiography -- t3. The Nation and Revolution: Narrating the Modern Event -- t4. Modernity as Political Discourse: Interpreting Revolution -- t5. The Spatial Logic of the New Culture: Modernity and Its Completion -- t6. Conclusion: Toward a Production of Anthropological Space -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book reexamines the historical thinking of Liang Qichao (1873-1929), one of the few modern Chinese thinkers and cultural critics whose appreciation of the question of modernity was based on first-hand experience of the world space in which China had to function as a nation-state. It seeks to demonstrate that Liang was not only a profoundly paradigmatic modern Chinese intellectual but also an imaginative thinker of worldwide significance. By tracing the changes in Liang's conception of history, the author shows that global space inspired both Liang's longing for modernity and his critical reconceptualization of modern history. Spatiality, or the mode of determining spatial organization and relationships, offers a new interpretive category for understanding the stages in Liang's historical thinking. Liang's historical thinking culminated in a global imaginary of difference, which became most evident in the shift from his earlier proposal for a uniform national history to one that mapped "cultural history." His reaffirmation of spatiality, a critical concept overshadowed by the modernist obsession with time and history, made it both necessary and possible for him to redesign the project of modernity. Finally, the author suggests that the reconciliation of anthropological space with historical time that Liang achieved makes him abundantly contemporary with our own time, both inextricably modern and postmodern.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311070421140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476474240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804764742423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804764742.jpg  a978-3-11-070421-1  SUP eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles